            "text_block_bCVMKc": {
              "type": "text-block",
              "name": "Text block",
              "settings": {
                "title": "Diamond color is graded on a scale from D (completely colorless) to Z (light yellow or brown). The difference between color grades is often subtle and nearly invisible to the untrained eye, particularly between adjacent grades. However, these small differences significantly impact a diamond's value and appearance. Colorless diamonds (D-F) are the most rare and valuable, appearing bright white and reflecting the most light. Near-colorless diamonds (G-J) still appear colorless to the naked eye but may show slight warmth under certain lighting. As you move further down the scale, diamonds begin to display increasingly visible yellow or brown tints. When set in jewelry, particularly in white gold or platinum, colorless diamonds create a striking, bright appearance that maximizes their fire and brilliance.",
                "font": "--font-family-second",
                "color": "#ffffff",
